df["Start_datetime"] = pd.to_datetime(df["Date"] + "/" + df["Start"]) #combine start date and time into one column
df["Max_datetime"] = pd.to_datetime(df["Date"] + "/" + df["Maximum"]) #combine max date and time into one column
df["End_datetime"] = pd.to_datetime(df["Date"] + "/" + df["End"]) #combine end date and time into one column
In [789]:
#update the dataframe using at command
for index, row in df.iterrows():
    df.at[index, "Start_datetime"]
for index, row in df.iterrows():
    df.at[index, "Max_datetime"]
for index, row in df.iterrows():
    df.at[index, "End_datetime"]

for i in range(12, len(save3)):
    new_temp = []
    temp = save3[i].split(" ") 
    #print("After splitting temp")
    #print(temp)

    data.append(new_temp)

#Question 1
# With the two datasets that we have for Top 50 Solar flares and NASA tables; we are basically trying to portray show how overlapping of data can be
# analyzed and seen.
# we have "part2q1solar1" dataframe which has data from Top 50 Soalr Flares.
# we have "final_nasa" datafrmae which has data from NASA table for top 50 based on their classfication.
# I believe they are not the same.
# For instance, when we have classification as X28; the regions do not match in both the datasets from NASA and Solar Flares.
# On the other hand, when we have a classification as X20, the regions do match in both the datasets from NASA and Solar Flares.
# Therefore, from this example we can say that they do not match though the start dates match but with the variances in time and the regions gives
# us the glance that the datasets do not match.

#Question 2
# The dataframe above is the data represented from NASA table.
# The dataframe contains those information which has a matching region in the Top 50 solar flares data set; basically doing a match over a region.
# Basically I have sorted data based on the classification and I match based on the region from both the datasets.
# So we have the data in f_data for all those classification which matches the region from the soalr flare table.
# I believe the best matching row would be the one with Classfication X2.7. I considered this as the best matching row based on the starting time
# and ending time in the sense the time taken (which is the difference between the start time and the end time). 
# It seems like it took them 10 minutes for X2.7 in the region 8210.
# If we take a look at the SpaceWeatherLive.com; we have multiple entries with X2.7; but I believe the one with region 2339 is the most efficient
# because the time difference between the start and end is 10 minutes which appears to be less than the classification X2.7 with the region 8210 which
# was one of our best matches in the above NASA table that we got based on matching regions from NASA and Top 50 Solar FLares datasets.
# Therefore, we observe that the data that we get based on same regions from the two datasets could have a different best row compared to SpaceWeatherLive.com
# as here we are determining based on the difference between the start and end times.
# To sum up, sorting on the basis of classification and matching based on the region and taking all those into account based on the time taken
# which we derive from the start time and end time is how I take solar flare and nasa datasets into consideration to find my best match.
